Roman Men and the Conspicuously Moral Masculinity of Scipio Aemilianus -- tPART III Ancient Meets Modern -- t14. Scipio Africanus and the Construction of Fascist Italian Masculinities -- t15. Insult to Injury: Senecan Stoicism, Misogyny and the Semantics of ‘Special Snowflake’ -- t16. Toxic Manhood Acts and the ‘Nice Guy’ Phenomenon in Ovid -- t17. Violence, Victimhood and the Rhetoric of Erotic Curses -- t18. ‘Legitimate Rape’ and Toxic Masculinity from Todd Akin to Soranus -- t19. Toxic Masculinity in the First-Year Classics Classroom -- tBibliography -- tIndex Locorum -- tIndex0 arestricted accessuhttp://purl.org/coar/access_right/c_16ecfonline access with authorization2star  aOffers the first study of toxic masculinity in the context of ancient Greece and RomeCovers both Greek and Roman societies, and a broad range of sources, such as curse tablets, history, philosophy, drama, poetry, and medical textsConnects the ancient and modern world to improve our understanding of bothAddresses contemporary issues and events such as violence against women and online hate groupsProvides a model for using anachronistic theoretical frameworks to understand the pastContributes to the field of masculinity studies by bringing together work on gender in ancient Greece, Rome, and contemporary Western societiesThis book looks at a contemporary concept – toxic masculinity – and considers its usefulness for understanding the ancient Mediterranean world. By concentrating on the particular elements that make up this form of masculine behaviour and identity, briefly defined as a performance of masculinity that is harmful to people who should be protected, to one’s community, or to oneself, we illuminate tensions and contradictions within Greek and Roman conceptions of gender, while tracing some origins of modern gender roles. This book also highlights the ways that texts and events from the ancient world are invoked in the construction of toxic masculinity today. Covering Athenian oratory and drama, Roman poetry and history, curse tablets, early Christian writing, Italian cinema, US politics, and more, this collection brings together the ancient and modern to ask what shapes a culture’s understanding of masculinity and how to identify the aspects of that understanding that can cause harm.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 02. Jun 2024) 0aMasculinityzGreecexHistoryyTo 1500. 4aClassics & Ancient History. 7aHISTORY / Ancient / General.2bisacsh1 aAgbamu, Samuel, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aAger, Britta, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aEvans, Jessica Penny, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aEvans, Rhiannon, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aGellar-Goad, T. H. M., econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aGoldberg, Charles, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aGoyette, Michael, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aHeydon, Kendell, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aHusby, Tristan K., econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aKenty, Joanna, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aKnight, Jayne, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aManwell, Elizabeth A., econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aMartorana, Simona, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aMarturano, Melissa, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aMasterson, Mark, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aMcMaster, Aven , eeditor.4edt4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/edt1 aMcM